b. Does this change seasonally? If so, how?¶

I created a interactive dashboard: heatmap + line chart over at https://1zhao.github.io/Vancouver/seasonal.html.¶

Across Vancouver’s neighbourhoods, abandoned waste clearly peaks in the summer months—mattress removals jump by over 50 percent and both small and large non‐recyclable dumps climb to their highest levels, with small non‐recyclables averaging about 105 per area compared to roughly 76 in winter. Spring and fall sit in the middle, while winter sees the lowest numbers across every category, especially recyclables and vehicle‐related waste.¶

In short, warm weather drives more illegal dumping across all waste types, and colder seasons bring everything down.¶

2) Show us all your steps and results including data loading, cleaning, analysis in one of these formats:¶

  • a. Python file; or
  • i. GitHub repository (optional)
  • b. PDF

3) Please include a short discussion (max 1-2 paragraphs) on any 1 of these questions:¶

a. What is interesting to you about this data?¶

The data intrigues me primarily due to its varying quality and diverse sources; notably, a significant portion lacks valid geometry, prompting questions about data collection methodologies and accuracy. I'm interested in how the spatial join process combines geometry-based matching with fuzzy text-based matches on neighborhood names, highlighting potential data quality issues. To enhance reliability, it would be valuable to implement consistent constraints ensuring all records have valid geometries, either through improved data collection via GPS-enabled apps or through mandatory field constraints at data entry points.

b. What additional information would you want to expand your analysis?¶

  • i. How would you acquire additional data required?

To expand my analysis further, I'd incorporate hotspot analyses using pure point data rather than relying solely on neighborhood boundaries, possibly applying machine learning algorithms to identify spatial clusters. Correlation analyses with supplementary datasets, such as crime incidents, would also provide deeper insights. Investigating data quality differences between web and mobile submissions, analyzing case resolution times, and understanding root causes behind prolonged case closures could greatly enrich the analysis and demonstrate the broader value of the dataset. I'd source additional crime incident data through open city geoportals or APIs, leveraging platforms like municipal data hubs or government open-data initiatives.

c. Any other observations, questions to explore, comments, or recommendations you have.¶

One key observation is that data cleaning and ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) processes consistently consume significant amounts of project time, particularly evident in the Van311 dataset. Additionally, I encountered issues with the Parquet format provided on the open data portal, prompting me to opt for GeoJSON files instead due to their reliability and ease of handling in my workflow. I'd recommend investing effort upfront in automating data cleaning tasks—using scripts and tools like Python and FME—to streamline future analyses and ensure more time is available for deeper exploratory and predictive analytics.

def clean_and_repair_geometries(gdf):
    original_count = len(gdf)
    cleaned_gdf = gdf.copy()
    
    invalid_geom_count = cleaned_gdf.geometry.isna().sum()
    if invalid_geom_count > 0:
        print(f"\nRemoving {invalid_geom_count} records with invalid geometries...")
        cleaned_gdf = cleaned_gdf[cleaned_gdf.geometry.notna()]
    
    invalid_shapes = ~cleaned_gdf.geometry.is_valid
    if invalid_shapes.any():
        print(f"\nRepairing {invalid_shapes.sum()} invalid geometries...")
        cleaned_gdf.geometry = cleaned_gdf.geometry.buffer(0)
    
    final_count = len(cleaned_gdf)
    print(f"\nCleaning complete:")
    print(f"Original records: {original_count}")
    print(f"Cleaned records: {final_count}")
    print(f"Removed records: {original_count - final_count}")
    
    return cleaned_gdf

cleaned_service_requests = clean_and_repair_geometries(service_requests)

6.Using regex to match¶

In [11]:
def clean_string(s):
    """Clean a string for fuzzy matching."""
    return '' if pd.isna(s) else re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9]', '', str(s).lower())

def find_best_match(source, targets):
    """Find best fuzzy match from a list of targets."""
    source_clean = clean_string(source)
    cleaned_targets = {clean_string(t): t for t in targets}
    if source_clean in cleaned_targets:
        return cleaned_targets[source_clean]
    for cleaned, original in cleaned_targets.items():
        if source_clean in cleaned or cleaned in source_clean:
            return original
    return None

def _apply_spatial_join(df, boundaries):
    """Perform spatial join for records with geometry."""
    subset = df[df.geometry.notna()].copy()
    joined = gpd.sjoin(subset, boundaries[['name', 'geometry']], how='left', predicate='within')
    df.loc[joined.index, 'matched_area_name'] = joined['name']
    matched = joined['name'].notna()
    df.loc[joined[matched].index, ['spatial_join_status', 'join_source']] = ['Y', 'geometry']
    return df

def _apply_regex_match(df, boundaries):
    """Fallback match using regex on 'local_area'."""
    names = boundaries['name'].unique().tolist()
    fallback = df.geometry.isna() & df['local_area'].notna()
    for i in df[fallback].index:
        match = find_best_match(df.at[i, 'local_area'], names)
        if match:
            df.loc[i, ['matched_area_name', 'spatial_join_status', 'join_source']] = [match, 'Y', 'Regex_name']
    return df

def process_spatial_join(points, boundaries):
    """Main function: spatial join with regex fallback."""
    df = points.copy()
    df[['spatial_join_status', 'join_source', 'matched_area_name']] = ['N', 'N/A', None]

    if df.geometry.notna().any():
        print(f"Processing {df.geometry.notna().sum()} records with valid geometry...")
        df = _apply_spatial_join(df, boundaries)

    if (df.geometry.isna() & df['local_area'].notna()).any():
        print(f"Processing {(df.geometry.isna() & df['local_area'].notna()).sum()} records using regex matching...")
        df = _apply_regex_match(df, boundaries)

    return df

def analyze_matching_results(processed_gdf, boundaries_gdf):
    # Overall statistics
    total_records = len(processed_gdf)
    successful_matches = (processed_gdf['spatial_join_status'] == 'Y').sum()
    failed_matches = (processed_gdf['spatial_join_status'] == 'N').sum()
    
    print(f"\nOverall Statistics:")
    print(f"Total records: {total_records}")
    print(f"Successful matches: {successful_matches} ({successful_matches/total_records*100:.2f}%)")
    print(f"Failed matches: {failed_matches} ({failed_matches/total_records*100:.2f}%)")
    
    # Join source breakdown
    print("\nJoin Source Breakdown:")
    source_counts = processed_gdf['join_source'].value_counts()
    for source, count in source_counts.items():
        print(f"{source}: {count} ({count/total_records*100:.2f}%)")
    
    # Analyze unmatched records
    unmatched = processed_gdf[processed_gdf['spatial_join_status'] == 'N']
    print("\nUnmatched Records Analysis:")
    print(f"Records without geometry: {unmatched.geometry.isna().sum()}")
    print(f"Records without local_area: {unmatched.local_area.isna().sum()}")

def tag_abandoned_waste(processed_data):
    # Filter only spatially joined records
    df = processed_data[processed_data['spatial_join_status'] == 'Y'].copy()

    # Define regex pattern to match 'abandoned' (case-insensitive)
    pattern = re.compile(r'abandoned', re.IGNORECASE)

    # Apply regex to create the 'abandoned_waste' flag
    df['abandoned_waste'] = df['service_request_type'].apply(
        lambda x: 'Y' if pattern.search(str(x)) else 'N'
    )

    return df

def flatten_abandoned_waste(boundaries, gdf):
    df = gdf[gdf["abandoned_waste"] == "Y"]
    counts = df.groupby(["matched_area_name", "service_request_type"]).size().reset_index(name="count")
    merged = boundaries.merge(counts, left_on="name", right_on="matched_area_name", how="left")
    wide = merged.pivot_table(index="name", columns="service_request_type", values="count", fill_value=0).reset_index()
    wide["total"] = wide.drop(columns="name").sum(axis=1)
    return boundaries.drop_duplicates("name")[["name", "geometry"]].merge(wide, on="name")

    Output("map", "figure"),
    Output("bar", "figure"),
    Input("waste_type", "value")
)
def update_charts(category):
    gdf["id"] = gdf.index.astype(str)  
    geojson = json.loads(gdf.to_json())

    gdf["hover"] = gdf.apply(lambda row: (
        f"<b>{row['name']}</b><br>" +
        "".join([f"{cat}: {int(row[cat])}<br>" for cat in categories[:-1]]) +
        f"<b>Total:</b> {int(row['total'])}"
    ), axis=1)
    
    fig_map = go.Figure(go.Choroplethmapbox(
        geojson=geojson,
        locations=gdf["id"],
        z=gdf[category],
        colorscale="YlOrRd",
        marker_opacity=0.75,
        marker_line_width=0.5,
        featureidkey="properties.id",
        hovertext=gdf["hover"],
        hoverinfo="text"
    ))


    fig_map.update_layout(
        mapbox_style="open-street-map",  # OSM base tiles
        mapbox_zoom=10.5,
        mapbox_center={"lat": 49.25, "lon": -123.1},
        margin={"r": 0, "t": 30, "l": 0, "b": 0},
        title=f"{category} by Neighbourhood"
    )

    # Bar chart
    fig_bar = px.bar(
        gdf.sort_values(by=category, ascending=False),
        x="name",
        y=category,
        labels={"name": "Neighbourhood", category: "Reports"},
        title="Neighbourhood Breakdown"
    )
    return fig_map, fig_bar

10.Extract the seasn by service_request_close_date¶

In [21]:
def abandoned_waste_season(boundaries, gdf):
    def season(d):
        m, d = d.month, d.day
        return ("Winter" if (m == 12 and d >= 21) or m in [1, 2] or (m == 3 and d < 21)
                else "Spring" if m < 6 or (m == 6 and d <= 21)
                else "Summer" if m < 9 or (m == 9 and d <= 22)
                else "Fall")

    df = gdf[gdf["abandoned_waste"] == "Y"].copy()
    df["season"] = pd.to_datetime(df["service_request_close_date"], errors="coerce").apply(season)

    agg = df.groupby(["matched_area_name", "service_request_type", "season"]).size().reset_index(name="count")
    merged = boundaries.merge(agg, left_on="name", right_on="matched_area_name", how="left")

    pivot = merged.pivot_table(index=["name", "season"], columns="service_request_type", values="count", fill_value=0).reset_index()
    value_cols = [col for col in pivot.columns if col not in ["name", "season"]]
    pivot["total"] = pivot[value_cols].sum(axis=1)

    return boundaries.drop_duplicates("name")[["name", "geometry"]].merge(pivot, on="name")

    dcc.Graph(id="heatmap"),
    dcc.Graph(id="linechart")
])


@app.callback(
    Output("heatmap", "figure"),
    Output("linechart", "figure"),
    Input("category", "value")
)
def update_visuals(category):
    pivot = categoried_abandoned_waste_season.pivot(index="season", columns="name", values=category).fillna(0)

    # Heatmap hover and emoji axis
    season_emoji = {"Winter": "❄️ Winter", "Spring": "🌸 Spring", "Summer": "☀️ Summer", "Fall": "🍂 Fall"}
    y_labels = [season_emoji.get(s, s) for s in pivot.index]

    hover_data = [[f"{category}<br>Season: {pivot.index[i]}<br>Neighbourhood: {col}<br>Count: {int(pivot.iloc[i,j])}"
                   for j, col in enumerate(pivot.columns)]
                  for i in range(len(pivot))]

    fig_heat = go.Figure(go.Heatmap(
        z=pivot.values,
        x=pivot.columns,
        y=y_labels,
        text=hover_data,
        hoverinfo="text",
        colorscale="YlOrRd"
    ))
    fig_heat.update_layout(
        title=f"{category} by Season and Neighbourhood",
        xaxis_title="Neighbourhood",
        yaxis_title="Season",
        xaxis_tickangle=-45
    )

    # Line chart (total reports per season)
    line_data = categoried_abandoned_waste_season.groupby("season")[category].sum().reset_index()
    line_data["season_emoji"] = line_data["season"].map(season_emoji)

    fig_line = px.line(
        line_data,
        x="season_emoji",
        y=category,
        markers=True,
        title=f"Total {category} Reports by Season",
        labels={category: "Report Count", "season_emoji": "Season"}
    )

    return fig_heat, fig_line



# Run the app
if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(debug=True, port=8052)

Part 2 “Quick Report”¶

You have been asked to write a “quick report” on active park litter container collection routes. The requester asked to view the containers that are part of the street litter (SL) collection routes and what days they are serviced. However, the data resides in different tables in the database.¶

Diagram 1 shows a relational data model with a small subset of records that are combined to create the output view in Table 1. Please write the SQL Query (select statement) required to join and filter the tables and get the output in Table 1.¶

SQL Query:¶

SELECT ca.ROUTE_ID,
    ca.CONTAINER_ID,
    lc.MODEL,
    lc.CAPACITY_L,
    lc.MATERIAL_DESC,
    rl.SERVICE_VEHICLE_TYPE,
    rl.PROJECT_ID,ca.SERVICE_DAY
FROM ContainerAllocation ca
JOIN LitterContainer lc ON ca.CONTAINER_ID = lc.CONTAINER_ID
JOIN RouteList rl ON ca.ROUTE_ID = rl.OBJECTID
WHERE ca.ROUTE_ID = 'SL_REC_SA'
    AND lc.STATUS = 'Active' 
    AND lc.MATERIAL_DESC = 'Recycling' -- can be removed if uncessary 
    AND rl.PROJECT_ID = 'SL' -- -- can be removed if uncessary 
    AND rl.SERVICE_VEHICLE_TYPE = 'SA' -- -- can be removed if uncessary 
ORDER BY ca.ROUTE_ID,
    ca.CONTAINER_ID,
    ca.SERVICE_DAY;
